# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: couple-mechanics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] In physics, **acceleration** is a measure of how fast and in what direction an object's speed and direction of motion are changing.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] It is defined as the rate of change of the velocity.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] Like velocity, acceleration has a magnitude and a direction, making it a vector quantity.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] The SI unit for acceleration is metre per second squared (m⋅s−2, m/s2).
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] The **tangential acceleration** of an object is the component of the **acceleration** which is in the same direction as the motion (or tangential velocity) of the object.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] When the velocity of the object does not change direction, this is called **linear acceleration**.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] **Deceleration** or **retardation**, on the other hand, is the component of the acceleration in the opposite (or antiparallel) direction to the tangential velocity.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] **Radial acceleration** or **normal acceleration** (or **centripetal acceleration** during circular motions) is the component of the acceleration that changes the direction of the object's velocity.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] In Newtonian mechanics, the acceleration of a mass arises from forces acting on it, with its *net* acceleration being a result of the *net* force acting on it.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] By Newton's second law, the magnitude of the *net* acceleration will be proportional to the magnitude of the *net* force acting on the object and inversely proportional to the mass of the object, while the direction of the *net* acceleration will be the same as the direction of the *net* force.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] An object's average acceleration ${\bar {\mathbf {a} }}$ over a period of time is its change in velocity, $\Delta \mathbf {v}$ , divided by the duration of the period, $\Delta t$ .
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] Mathematically, ${\bar {\mathbf {a} }}={\frac {\Delta \mathbf {v} }{\Delta t}}.$ The average acceleration is the simplest way to measure acceleration, requiring only knowledge of the change in velocity and the change in time.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] In a strict sense, the average acceleration is the only *true* acceleration one is able to directly measure without appealing to an empirical law, meaning that it is the most fundamental form of acceleration measurement.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] The average acceleration is most often used to approximate the kinematics of an object by assuming that the velocity changes linearly with time.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] Instantaneous acceleration is the limit of the average acceleration over an infinitesimal interval of time.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] Acceleration has the dimensions of velocity (L/T) divided by time, i.e.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] The SI unit of acceleration is the metre per second squared (m s−2); or "metre per second per second", as the velocity in metres per second changes by the acceleration value, every second.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] An object moving in a circular motion—such as a satellite orbiting the Earth—is accelerating due to the change of direction of motion, although its speed may be constant.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] In this case it is said to be undergoing *centripetal* (directed towards the center) acceleration.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] Proper acceleration, the acceleration of a body relative to a free-fall condition, is measured by an instrument called an accelerometer.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] Newton's second law is normally applied in an inertial reference frame.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] In a reference frame accelerating with acceleration a (in one dimension), Newton's laws can still be used by introducing an inertial force (fictitious force) $F=-ma$ on a mass m , opposite the acceleration of the frame.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] This accounts for the tendency of the mass to maintain its inertial motion—to stay "as is," at rest or moving at constant velocity—while the frame accelerates.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] One example is that a person in an elevator feels heavier or lighter as the elevator accelerates or decelerates.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] If m is known, measurement of the supporting force on the mass can be used to infer the acceleration; this is the principle of a mechanical accelerometer.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] In general relativity, gravity and inertial acceleration may be locally indistinguishable (see General relativity).
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] As speeds approach the speed of light, relativistic effects become increasingly large.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] When a vehicle starts from a standstill (zero velocity, in an inertial frame of reference) and travels in a straight line at increasing speeds, it is accelerating in the direction of travel.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] If the vehicle turns, an acceleration occurs toward the new direction and changes its motion vector.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] The component of acceleration of the vehicle in the direction of its velocity is called a **linear acceleration** or **tangential acceleration**, its effect being the passengers on board experience as a fictitious force pushing them back into or away from their seats.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] When changing direction, the component of the acceleration perpendicular to the velocity is called **radial** or **normal acceleration** (or **centripetal acceleration** during circular motion), the reaction to which the passengers experience as a centrifugal force (another fictitious force).
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] If the speed of the vehicle decreases, this is an acceleration in the opposite direction of the velocity vector, sometimes called **deceleration** or **retardation**, and passengers experience the reaction to deceleration as an inertial force pushing them forward.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] Such deceleration is often achieved by retrorocket burning in spacecraft.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] Both acceleration and deceleration are treated the same, as they are both changes in velocity.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] Each of these accelerations (tangential, radial, deceleration) is felt by passengers until their relative (differential) velocity is neutralised in reference to the acceleration due to change in speed.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] where **u**n is the unit (inward) normal vector to the particle's trajectory (also called *the principal normal*), and **r** is its instantaneous radius of curvature based upon the osculating circle at time t.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] Geometrical analysis of three-dimensional space curves, which explains tangent, (principal) normal and binormal, is described by the Frenet–Serret formulas.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] A frequently cited example of uniform acceleration is that of an object in free fall in a uniform gravitational field.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] The acceleration of a falling body in the absence of resistances to motion is dependent only on the gravitational field strength g (also called *acceleration due to gravity*).
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] In particular, the motion can be resolved into two orthogonal parts, one of constant velocity and the other according to the above equations.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] As Galileo showed, the net result is parabolic motion, which describes, e.g., the trajectory of a projectile in vacuum near the surface of Earth.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] , always points radially from the origin.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] , not parallel to the radial motion but offset by the angular and Coriolis accelerations, nor tangent to the path but offset by the centripetal and radial accelerations.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] plane in a point of an arbitrary curve in any higher dimension.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] In uniform circular motion, that is moving with constant *speed* along a circular path, a particle experiences an acceleration resulting from the change of the direction of the velocity vector, while its magnitude remains constant.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] The derivative of the location of a point on a curve with respect to time, i.e. its velocity, turns out to be always exactly tangential to the curve, respectively orthogonal to the radius in this point.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] Since in uniform motion the velocity in the tangential direction does not change, the acceleration must be in radial direction, pointing to the center of the circle.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] This acceleration constantly changes the direction of the velocity to be tangent in the neighbouring point, thereby rotating the velocity vector along the circle.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] This acceleration and the mass of the particle determine the necessary centripetal force, directed *toward* the centre of the circle, as the net force acting on this particle to keep it in this uniform circular motion.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] The so-called 'centrifugal force', appearing to act outward on the body, is a so-called pseudo force experienced in the frame of reference of the body in circular motion, due to the body's linear momentum, a vector tangent to the circle of motion.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] The tangential component is given by the angular acceleration $\alpha$ , i.e., the rate of change $\alpha ={\dot {\omega }}$ of the angular speed $\omega$ times the radius r .
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] The sign of the tangential component of the acceleration is determined by the sign of the angular acceleration ( $\alpha$ ), and the tangent is always directed at right angles to the radius vector.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] In multi-dimensional Cartesian coordinate systems, acceleration is broken up into components that correspond with each dimensional axis of the coordinate system.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] The special theory of relativity describes the behaviour of objects travelling relative to other objects at speeds approaching that of light in vacuum.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] Newtonian mechanics is exactly revealed to be an approximation to reality, valid to great accuracy at lower speeds.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] As the relevant speeds increase toward the speed of light, acceleration no longer follows classical equations.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] As speeds approach that of light, the acceleration produced by a given force decreases, becoming infinitesimally small as light speed is approached; an object with mass can approach this speed asymptotically, but never reach it.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] Unless the state of motion of an object is known, it is impossible to distinguish whether an observed force is due to gravity or to acceleration—gravity and inertial acceleration have identical effects.
[src:couple-mechanics/acceleration] Albert Einstein called this the equivalence principle, and said that only observers who feel no force at all—including the force of gravity—are justified in concluding that they are not accelerating.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] Clairaut was born in Paris, France, to Jean-Baptiste and Catherine Petit Clairaut.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] The couple had 20 children, however only a few of them survived childbirth.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] He mastered Euclidean geometry and algebra by nine.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] At ten he studied conic sections and the calculus using *Analyse des Infiniment Petits* (1696) by Guillaume de l'Hôpital.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] At the age of twelve he wrote a memoir on four geometrical curves and under his father's tutelage he made such rapid progress in the subject that in his thirteenth year he read before the Académie française an account of the properties of four curves which he had discovered.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] When only sixteen he finished a treatise on Tortuous Curves, *Recherches sur les courbes a double courbure*, which, on its publication in 1731, procured his admission into the Royal Academy of Sciences, although he was below the legal age as he was only eighteen.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] He gave a path-breaking formulae called the distance formulae which helps to find out the distance between any 2 points on the cartesian or XY plane.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] Clairaut never married and known for leading an active social life.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] He was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society of London on 27 October 1737.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] In his research on the calculus, Clairaut discovered the equality of mixed partial derivatives (Clairaut's theorem).
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] He gave a condition under which the differential equation $M(x,y)\,dx+N(x,y)\,dy=0$ was exact, namely, $M_{y}=N_{x}$ .
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] He showed that a differential equation of the form $y=xy'+f(y')$ , now known as Clairaut's equation, could by solved by substituting $p=y'$ and differentiating both sides.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] He also established the existence of the integrating factor for first-order linear differential equations.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] However, he had been anticipated by Nicolas Fatio de Dullier in 1687, and by Johann Bernoulli in a lesson given to L’Hôpital.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] In 1741, Clairaut published *Éléments de Géométrie*, aimed at beginners.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] For Clairaut, it was imperative for students to make discoveries themselves in a form of active, experiential learning.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] He began by comparing geometric shapes to measurements of land, a familiar topic, and covered lines, shapes, and even some three dimensional objects.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] Throughout the book, he copiously related geometry to other branches of mathematics as well as physics and astronomy.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] Some of the theories and learning methods outlined in the book are still used by teachers today, in geometry and other topics.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] This textbook was so popular that it went through six editions.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] In the eighteenth century, Carl Friedrich Gauss extended the contributions of Clairaut and Christiaan Huygens in the geometry introducing the notion of Gaussian curvature.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] Clairaut's *Éléments de Algèbre* (1740) was also well-received in Continental Europe.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] Its sixth edition was published in 1801.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] In 1736, together with Pierre Louis Maupertuis, he took part in the expedition to Lapland, which was undertaken for the purpose of estimating a degree of the meridian arc.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] The goal of the excursion was to determine the figure of the Earth and to test whether the Earth was an oblate spheroid, as Sir Isaac Newton had claimed in his book *Principia*, or that it was an oblong, as Giovanni Cassini had thought.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] Before the expedition team returned to Paris, Clairaut sent his calculations to the Royal Society of London.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] The writing was later published by the society in the 1736–37 volume of *Philosophical Transactions.* Initially, Clairaut disagreed with Newton's conclusion.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] In the article, he outlines several key problems that effectively disprove Newton's calculations, and provides some solutions to the complications.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] The issues addressed include calculating gravitational attraction, the rotation of an ellipsoid on its axis, and the difference in density of an ellipsoid on its axes.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] This meant not only that the Earth is an ellipsoid, but it is flattened more at the poles and is wider at the center, that is, an oblate spheroid.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] His article in *Philosophical Transactions* created much controversy, as he addressed the problems of Newton's theory, but provided few solutions to how to fix the calculations.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] After his return, he published his treatise *Théorie de la figure de la terre* (1743).
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] In this work he promulgated a result, now known as Clairaut's theorem, which connects the gravity at points on the surface of a rotating ellipsoid with the compression and the centrifugal force at the equator.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] His formula gave the Earth's gravitational field strength as a function of latitude.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] Under the assumption that the Earth was composed of concentric ellipsoidal shells of uniform density, Clairaut's theorem could be applied to it, and allowed the eccentricity (or deviation from being a perfect sphere) of the Earth to be calculated from surface measurements of gravity.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] In 1849 George Stokes showed that Clairaut's result was true whatever the interior constitution or density of the Earth, provided the surface was a spheroid of equilibrium of small eccentricity.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] One of the most controversial issues of the 18th century was the problem of three bodies, or how the Earth, Moon, and Sun are attracted to one another.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] With the use of the recently founded Leibnizian calculus, Clairaut was able to solve the problem using four differential equations.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] He was also able to incorporate Newton's inverse-square law and law of attraction into his solution, with minor edits to it.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] However, these equations only offered approximate measurement, and no exact calculations.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] Another issue still remained with the three body problem; how the Moon rotates on its apsides.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] Even Newton could account for only half of the motion of the apsides.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] In fact, Clairaut had at first deemed the dilemma so inexplicable, that he was on the point of publishing a new hypothesis as to the law of attraction.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] The question of the apsides was a heated debate topic in Europe.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] Along with Clairaut, there were two other mathematicians who were racing to provide the first explanation for the three body problem; Leonhard Euler and Jean le Rond d'Alembert.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] Euler and d'Alembert were arguing against the use of Newtonian laws to solve the three-body problem.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] Euler in particular believed that the inverse square law needed revision to accurately calculate the apsides of the Moon.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] Despite the hectic competition to come up with the correct solution, Clairaut obtained an ingenious approximate solution of the problem of the three bodies.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] In 1750 he gained the prize of the St Petersburg Academy for his essay *Théorie de la lune*; the team made up of Clairaut, Jérome Lalande and Nicole Reine Lepaute successfully computed the date of the 1759 return of Halley's comet.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] The *Théorie de la lune* is strictly Newtonian in character.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] This contains the explanation of the motion of the apsis.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] It occurred to him to carry the approximation to the third order, and he thereupon found that the result was in accordance with the observations.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] This was followed in 1754 by some lunar tables, which he computed using a form of the discrete Fourier transform.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] The newfound solution to the problem of three bodies ended up meaning more than proving Newton's laws correct.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] The unravelling of the problem of three bodies also had practical importance.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] It allowed sailors to determine the longitudinal direction of their ships, which was crucial not only in sailing to a location, but finding their way home as well.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] This held economic implications as well, because sailors were able to more easily find destinations of trade based on the longitudinal measures.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] In the same work, Clairaut introduced for the first time the theory of potentials, known by that name since the 1828 essay of George Green.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] Clairaut subsequently wrote various papers on the orbit of the Moon, and on the motion of comets as affected by the perturbation of the planets, particularly on the path of Halley's comet.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] He also used applied mathematics to study Venus, taking accurate measurements of the planet's size and distance from the Earth.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] This was the first precise reckoning of the planet's size.
[src:couple-mechanics/alexis-clairaut] Clairaut used his own contributions to celestial mechanics and astronomy to assist Émilie du Châtelet in her translation and commentary of Newton's *Principia*.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] In theoretical physics and mathematical physics, **analytical mechanics**, or **theoretical mechanics** is a collection of closely related formulations of classical mechanics.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Analytical mechanics uses *scalar* properties of motion representing the system as a whole—usually its kinetic energy and potential energy.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] The equations of motion are derived from the scalar quantity by some underlying principle about the scalar's variation.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Analytical mechanics was developed by many scientists and mathematicians during the 18th century and onward, after Newtonian mechanics.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Newtonian mechanics considers vector quantities of motion, particularly accelerations, momenta, forces, of the constituents of the system; it can also be called *vectorial mechanics*.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] A scalar is a quantity, whereas a vector is represented by quantity and direction.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] The results of these two different approaches are equivalent, but the analytical mechanics approach has many advantages for complex problems.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Analytical mechanics takes advantage of a system's *constraints* to solve problems.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] The constraints limit the degrees of freedom the system can have, and can be used to reduce the number of coordinates needed to solve for the motion.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] The formalism is well suited to arbitrary choices of coordinates, known in the context as generalized coordinates.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] The kinetic and potential energies of the system are expressed using these generalized coordinates or momenta, and the equations of motion can be readily set up, thus analytical mechanics allows numerous mechanical problems to be solved with greater efficiency than fully vectorial methods.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] It does not always work for non-conservative forces or dissipative forces like friction, in which case one may revert to Newtonian mechanics.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Two dominant branches of analytical mechanics are Lagrangian mechanics (using generalized coordinates and corresponding generalized velocities in configuration space) and Hamiltonian mechanics (using coordinates and corresponding momenta in phase space).
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Both formulations are equivalent by a Legendre transformation on the generalized coordinates, velocities and momenta; therefore, both contain the same information for describing the dynamics of a system.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] There are other formulations such as Hamilton–Jacobi theory, Routhian mechanics, and Appell's equation of motion.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] All equations of motion for particles and fields, in any formalism, can be derived from the widely applicable result called the principle of least action.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] One result is Noether's theorem, a statement which connects conservation laws to their associated symmetries.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Analytical mechanics does not introduce new physics and is not more general than Newtonian mechanics.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Rather it is a collection of equivalent formalisms which have broad application.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] In fact the same principles and formalisms can be used in relativistic mechanics and general relativity, and with some modifications, quantum mechanics and quantum field theory.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Analytical mechanics is used widely, from fundamental physics to applied mathematics, particularly chaos theory.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] The methods of analytical mechanics apply to discrete particles, each with a finite number of degrees of freedom.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] They can be modified to describe continuous fields or fluids, which have infinite degrees of freedom.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] The definitions and equations have a close analogy with those of mechanics.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] The goal of mechanical theory is to solve mechanical problems, such as arise in physics and engineering.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Starting from a physical system—such as a mechanism or a star system—a mathematical model is developed in the form of a differential equation.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] The model can be solved numerically or analytically to determine the motion of the system.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Newton's vectorial approach to mechanics describes motion with the help of vector quantities such as force, velocity, acceleration.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] These quantities characterise the motion of a body idealised as a "mass point" or a "particle" understood as a single point to which a mass is attached.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Newton's method has been successfully applied to a wide range of physical problems, including the motion of a particle in Earth's gravitational field and the motion of planets around the Sun.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] In this approach, Newton's laws describe the motion by a differential equation and then the problem is reduced to the solving of that equation.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] When a mechanical system contains many particles, however (such as a complex mechanism or a fluid), Newton's approach is difficult to apply.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Using a Newtonian approach is possible, under proper precautions, namely isolating each single particle from the others, and determining all the forces acting on it.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Such analysis is cumbersome even in relatively simple systems.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Newton thought that his third law "action equals reaction" would take care of all complications.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] This is false even for such simple system as rotations of a solid body.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] In more complicated systems, the vectorial approach cannot give an adequate description.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] The analytical approach simplifies problems by treating mechanical systems as ensembles of particles that interact with each other, rather considering each particle as an isolated unit.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] In the vectorial approach, forces must be determined individually for each particle, whereas in the analytical approach it is enough to know one single function which contains implicitly all the forces acting on and in the system.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Such simplification is often done using certain kinematic conditions which are stated *a priori*.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] However, the analytical treatment does not require the knowledge of these forces and takes these kinematic conditions for granted.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Still, deriving the equations of motion of a complicated mechanical system requires a unifying basis from which they follow.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] This is provided by various variational principles: behind each set of equations there is a principle that expresses the meaning of the entire set.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Given a fundamental and universal quantity called *action*, the principle that this action be stationary under small variation of some other mechanical quantity generates the required set of differential equations.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] The statement of the principle does not require any special coordinate system, and all results are expressed in generalized coordinates.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] This means that the analytical equations of motion do not change upon a coordinate transformation, an invariance property that is lacking in the vectorial equations of motion.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] It is not altogether clear what is meant by 'solving' a set of differential equations.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] A problem is regarded as solved when the particles coordinates at time *t* are expressed as simple functions of *t* and of parameters defining the initial positions and velocities.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] If one speaks merely of 'functions', then every mechanical problem is solved as soon as it has been well stated in differential equations, because given the initial conditions and *t* determine the coordinates at *t*.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] This is a fact especially at present with the modern methods of computer modelling which provide arithmetical solutions to mechanical problems to any desired degree of accuracy, the differential equations being replaced by difference equations.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Still, though lacking precise definitions, it is obvious that the two-body problem has a simple solution, whereas the three-body problem has not.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] The two-body problem is solved by formulas involving parameters; their values can be changed to study the class of all solutions, that is, the mathematical structure of the problem.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Moreover, an accurate mental or drawn picture can be made for the motion of two bodies, and it can be as real and accurate as the real bodies moving and interacting.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] In the three-body problem, parameters can also be assigned specific values; however, the solution at these assigned values or a collection of such solutions does not reveal the mathematical structure of the problem.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] As in many other problems, the mathematical structure can be elucidated only by examining the differential equations themselves.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Analytical mechanics aims at even more: not at understanding the mathematical structure of a single mechanical problem, but that of a class of problems so wide that they encompass most of mechanics.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] It concentrates on systems to which Lagrangian or Hamiltonian equations of motion are applicable and that include a very wide range of problems indeed.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Development of analytical mechanics has two objectives: (i) increase the range of solvable problems by developing standard techniques with a wide range of applicability, and (ii) understand the mathematical structure of mechanics.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] In the long run, however, (ii) can help (i) more than a concentration on specific problems for which methods have already been designed.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] In Newtonian mechanics, one customarily uses all three Cartesian coordinates, or other 3D coordinate system, to refer to a body's position during its motion.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] In physical systems, however, some structure or other system usually constrains the body's motion from taking certain directions and pathways.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] So a full set of Cartesian coordinates is often unneeded, as the constraints determine the evolving relations among the coordinates, which relations can be modeled by equations corresponding to the constraints.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] In the Lagrangian and Hamiltonian formalisms, the constraints are incorporated into the motion's geometry, reducing the number of coordinates to the minimum needed to model the motion.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] These are known as *generalized coordinates*, denoted *qi* (*i* = 1, 2, 3...).
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Generalized coordinates incorporate constraints on the system.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] There is one generalized coordinate *qi* for each degree of freedom (for convenience labelled by an index *i* = 1, 2...*N*), i.e. each way the system can change its configuration; as curvilinear lengths or angles of rotation.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Generalized coordinates are not the same as curvilinear coordinates.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] D'Alembert's principle states that infinitesimal *virtual work* done by a force across reversible displacements is zero, which is the work done by a force consistent with ideal constraints of the system.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] The idea of a constraint is useful – since this limits what the system can do, and can provide steps to solving for the motion of the system.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Vector **r** is explicitly dependent on *t* in cases when the constraints vary with time, not just because of **q**(*t*).
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] For time-independent situations, the constraints are also called **scleronomic**, for time-dependent cases they are called **rheonomic**.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] which are a set of *N* second-order ordinary differential equations, one for each *qi*(*t*).
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] This formulation identifies the actual path followed by the motion as a selection of the path over which the time integral of kinetic energy is least, assuming the total energy to be fixed, and imposing no conditions on the time of transit.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] where $\mathbb {R} ^{N}$ is *N*-dimensional real space (see also set-builder notation).
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] The particular solution to the Euler–Lagrange equations is called a *(configuration) path or trajectory*, i.e. one particular **q**(*t*) subject to the required initial conditions.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] The configuration space can be defined more generally, and indeed more deeply, in terms of topological manifolds and the tangent bundle.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] which are now a set of 2*N* first-order ordinary differential equations, one for each *qi*(*t*) and *pi*(*t*).
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] which is often considered one of Hamilton's equations of motion additionally to the others.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] that is, the Cartesian product of the configuration space and generalized momentum space.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] A particular solution to Hamilton's equations is called a *phase path*, a particular curve (**q**(*t*),**p**(*t*)) subject to the required initial conditions.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] All dynamical variables can be derived from position **q**, momentum **p**, and time *t*, and written as a function of these: *A* = *A*(**q**, **p**, *t*).
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Following are overlapping properties between the Lagrangian and Hamiltonian functions.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] where the departure *t*1 and arrival *t*2 times are fixed.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] The term "path" or "trajectory" refers to the time evolution of the system as a path through configuration space ${\mathcal {C}}$ , in other words **q**(*t*) tracing out a path in ${\mathcal {C}}$ .
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] The path for which action is least is the path taken by the system.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] From this principle, *all* equations of motion in classical mechanics can be derived.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] This approach can be extended to fields rather than a system of particles (see below), and underlies the path integral formulation of quantum mechanics, and is used for calculating geodesic motion in general relativity.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] the above transformations are called *canonical transformations*, each function *Gn* is called a generating function of the "*n*th kind" or "type-*n*".
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] The transformation of coordinates and momenta can allow simplification for solving Hamilton's equations for a given problem.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] The choice of **Q** and **P** is completely arbitrary, but not every choice leads to a canonical transformation.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] If this does not hold then the transformation is not canonical.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] used to solve the HJE by additive separation of variables for a time-independent Hamiltonian *H*.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] The study of the solutions of the Hamilton–Jacobi equations leads naturally to the study of symplectic manifolds and symplectic topology.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] In this formulation, the solutions of the Hamilton–Jacobi equations are the integral curves of Hamiltonian vector fields.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Routhian mechanics is a hybrid formulation of Lagrangian and Hamiltonian mechanics, not often used but especially useful for removing cyclic coordinates.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] If the Lagrangian of a system has *s* cyclic coordinates **q** = *q*1, *q*2, ...
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] and *N* − *s* Lagrangian equations in the non cyclic coordinates **ζ**.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Set up in this way, although the Routhian has the form of the Hamiltonian, it can be thought of a Lagrangian with *N* − *s* degrees of freedom.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] The coordinates **q** do not have to be cyclic, the partition between which coordinates enter the Hamiltonian equations and those which enter the Lagrangian equations is arbitrary.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] It is simply convenient to let the Hamiltonian equations remove the cyclic coordinates, leaving the non cyclic coordinates to the Lagrangian equations of motion.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] as well as generalized forces mentioned above in D'Alembert's principle.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] is the acceleration of the *k* particle, the second time derivative of its position vector.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Each acceleration **a***k* is expressed in terms of the generalized accelerations *αr*, likewise each **r**k are expressed in terms the generalized coordinates *qr*.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Generalized coordinates apply to discrete particles.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] For *N* scalar fields, these Lagrangian field equations are a set of *N* second order partial differential equations in the fields, which in general will be coupled and nonlinear.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] This scalar field formulation can be extended to vector fields, tensor fields, and spinor fields.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Originally developed for classical fields, the above formulation is applicable to all physical fields in classical, quantum, and relativistic situations: such as Newtonian gravity, classical electromagnetism, general relativity, and quantum field theory.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] It is a question of determining the correct Lagrangian density to generate the correct field equation.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] For *N* fields, these Hamiltonian field equations are a set of 2*N* first order partial differential equations, which in general will be coupled and nonlinear.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] Each transformation can be described by an operator (i.e. function acting on the position **r** or momentum **p** variables to change them).
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] The following are the cases when the operator does not change **r** or **p**, i.e. symmetries.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] where *R*(**n̂**, θ) is the rotation matrix about an axis defined by the unit vector **n̂** and angle θ.
[src:couple-mechanics/analytical-mechanics] The corresponding momenta to *q* will be conserved.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-acceleration] In kinematics, **angular acceleration** (symbol ***α***, alpha) is the time derivative of angular velocity.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-acceleration] Angular acceleration has physical dimensions of inverse time squared, with the SI unit **radian per second squared** (**rad⋅s−2**).
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-acceleration] In two dimensions, angular acceleration is a pseudoscalar whose sign is taken to be positive if the angular speed increases counterclockwise or decreases clockwise, and is taken to be negative if the angular speed increases clockwise or decreases counterclockwise.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-acceleration] In three dimensions, angular acceleration is a pseudovector.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-acceleration] In two dimensions, the orbital angular acceleration is the rate at which the two-dimensional orbital angular velocity of the particle about the origin changes.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-acceleration] where r is the distance from the origin and $v_{\perp }$ is the cross-radial component of the instantaneous velocity (i.e. the component perpendicular to the position vector), which by convention is positive for counter-clockwise motion and negative for clockwise motion.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-acceleration] In two dimensions, angular acceleration is a number with plus or minus sign indicating orientation, but not pointing in a direction.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-acceleration] The sign is conventionally taken to be positive if the angular speed increases in the counter-clockwise direction or decreases in the clockwise direction, and the sign is taken negative if the angular speed increases in the clockwise direction or decreases in the counter-clockwise direction.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-acceleration] Angular acceleration then may be termed a pseudoscalar, a numerical quantity which changes sign under a parity inversion, such as inverting one axis or switching the two axes.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-acceleration] In three dimensions, the orbital angular acceleration is the rate at which three-dimensional orbital angular velocity vector changes with time.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-acceleration] where $\mathbf {r}$ is the particle's position vector, r its distance from the origin, and $\mathbf {v}$ its velocity vector.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-acceleration] Since $\mathbf {r} \times \mathbf {v}$ is just $r^{2}{\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ , the second term may be rewritten as $\textstyle -{\frac {2}{r}}{\frac {dr}{dt}}{\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ .
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-acceleration] This cannot not happen if the position vector is restricted to a fixed plane, in which case ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ has a fixed direction perpendicular to the plane.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-acceleration] The angular acceleration vector is more properly called a pseudovector: It has three components which transform under rotations in the same way as the Cartesian coordinates of a point do, but which do not transform like Cartesian coordinates under reflections.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-acceleration] where $\mathbf {F}$ is the net force on the particle.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-acceleration] Torque is the rotational analogue of force: it induces change in the rotational state of a system, just as force induces change in the translational state of a system.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-acceleration] As force on a particle is connected to acceleration by the equation $\mathbf {F} =m\mathbf {a}$ , one may write a similar equation connecting torque on a particle to angular acceleration, though this relation is necessarily more complicated.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-acceleration] where ${\boldsymbol {\alpha }}$ is orbital angular acceleration and ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ is orbital angular velocity.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-acceleration] which can be interpreted as a "rotational analogue" to $\mathbf {F} =m\mathbf {a}$ , where the quantity $mr^{2}$ (known as the moment of inertia of the particle) plays the role of the mass m .
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-acceleration] However, unlike $\mathbf {F} =m\mathbf {a}$ , this equation does *not* apply to an arbitrary trajectory, only to a trajectory contained within a spherical shell about the origin.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] Angular displacement may be signed, indicating the direction of rotation (e.g., clockwise versus counterclockwise); it may also be greater (in absolute value) than a full turn if the rotation was.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] When a body with orientation rotates about an axis, the motion of the orientation must be taken into account, such as how the yaw, pitch and roll of a plane all result in different, new orientations.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] Each part of the object experiences circular motion as it undergoes the rotation.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] The simplest case is that of the rigid body in which the object itself does not change.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] Precisely, this is when the distances between all the particles remain constant throughout the body's motion, as opposed to it having internally moving parts parts or accumulating or releasing parts of itself.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] Many real bodies are approximated as rigid bodies, such as airplanes in flight simulations.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] In the example illustrated to the left (or above in some mobile versions), a particle or body P is at a fixed distance *r* from the origin, *O*, rotating counterclockwise.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] It becomes important to then represent the position of particle P in terms of its polar coordinates (*r*, *θ*).
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] In this particular example, the value of *θ* is changing, while the value of the radius remains the same.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] Angular displacement may be expressed with the unit radian or degree.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] For example, if a body rotates 360° around a circle of radius *r*, the angular displacement is given by the distance traveled around the circumference - which is 2π*r* - divided by the radius: $\theta ={\frac {2\pi r}{r}}$ which easily simplifies to: $\theta =2\pi$ .
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] Therefore, 1 revolution is $2\pi$ radians.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] The above definition is part of the International System of Quantities (ISQ), formalized in the international standard ISO 80000-3 (Space and time), and adopted in the International System of Units (SI).
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] Angular displacement may be signed, indicating the sense of rotation (e.g., clockwise); it may also be greater (in absolute value) than a full turn.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] In the ISQ/SI, angular displacement is used to define the *number of revolutions*, *N* = θ/(2π rad), a ratio and hence a quantity of dimension one.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] In three dimensions, angular displacement is an entity with a direction and a magnitude.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] The direction specifies the axis of rotation, which always exists by virtue of the Euler's rotation theorem; the magnitude specifies the rotation in radians about that axis (using the right-hand rule to determine direction).
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] Despite having direction and magnitude, angular displacement is not a vector because it does not obey the commutative law for addition.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] Nevertheless, when dealing with infinitesimal rotations, second order infinitesimals can be discarded and in this case commutativity appears.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] Several ways to describe rotations exist, like rotation matrices or Euler angles.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] Given that any frame in the space can be described by a rotation matrix, the displacement among them can also be described by a rotation matrix.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] Being $A_{0}$ and $A_{f}$ two matrices, the angular displacement matrix between them can be obtained as ⁠ $\Delta A=A_{f}A_{0}^{-1}$ ⁠.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] When this product is performed having a very small difference between both frames we will obtain a matrix close to the identity.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] In the limit, we will have an infinitesimal rotation matrix.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] An infinitesimal rotation matrix or differential rotation matrix is a matrix representing an infinitely small rotation.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] where I is the identity matrix, $d\theta$ is vanishingly small, and ⁠ $A\in {\mathfrak {so}}(n)$ ⁠.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] The computation rules for infinitesimal rotation matrices are the usual ones except that infinitesimals of second order are dropped.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] With these rules, these matrices do not satisfy all the same properties as ordinary finite rotation matrices under the usual treatment of infinitesimals.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-displacement] It turns out that *the order in which infinitesimal rotations are applied is irrelevant*.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-frequency] Angular frequency (or angular speed) is the magnitude of the pseudovector quantity *angular velocity*.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-frequency] Angular frequency can be obtained by multiplying *rotational frequency*, *ν* (or ordinary *frequency*, *f*) by a full turn (2π radians): *ω* = 2π rad⋅*ν*.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-frequency] It can also be formulated as *ω* = d*θ*/d*t*, the instantaneous rate of change of the angular displacement, *θ*, with respect to time, *t*.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-frequency] In SI units, angular frequency is normally presented in the unit radian per second.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-frequency] The unit hertz (Hz) is dimensionally equivalent, but by convention it is only used for frequency *f*, never for angular frequency *ω*.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-frequency] This convention is used to help avoid the confusion that arises when dealing with quantities such as frequency and angular quantities because the units of measure (such as cycle or radian) are considered to be one and hence may be omitted when expressing quantities in terms of SI units.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-frequency] In digital signal processing, the frequency may be normalized by the sampling rate, yielding the normalized frequency.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-frequency] In a rotating or orbiting object, there is a relation between distance from the axis, r , tangential speed, v , and the angular frequency of the rotation.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-frequency] During one period, T , a body in circular motion travels a distance $vT$ .
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-frequency] This distance is also equal to the circumference of the path traced out by the body, $2\pi r$ .
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-frequency] An object attached to a spring can oscillate.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-frequency] As the object oscillates, its acceleration can be calculated by $a=-\omega ^{2}x,$ where *x* is displacement from an equilibrium position.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-frequency] Adding series resistance (for example, due to the resistance of the wire in a coil) does not change the resonant frequency of the series LC circuit.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-frequency] For a parallel tuned circuit, the above equation is often a useful approximation, but the resonant frequency does depend on the losses of parallel elements.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-frequency] Although angular frequency is often loosely referred to as frequency, it differs from frequency by a factor of 2π, which potentially leads confusion when the distinction is not made clear.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The three-dimensional angular momentum for a point particle is classically represented as a pseudovector **r** × **p**, the cross product of the particle's position vector **r** (relative to some origin) and its momentum vector; the latter is **p** = *m***v** in Newtonian mechanics.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Unlike linear momentum, angular momentum depends on where this origin is chosen, since the particle's position is measured from it.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Angular momentum is an extensive quantity; that is, the total angular momentum of any composite system is the sum of the angular momenta of its constituent parts.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] For a continuous rigid body or a fluid, the total angular momentum is the volume integral of angular momentum density (angular momentum per unit volume in the limit as volume shrinks to zero) over the entire body.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Similar to conservation of linear momentum, where it is conserved if there is no external force, angular momentum is conserved if there is no external torque.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Torque can be defined as the rate of change of angular momentum, analogous to force.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The net *external* torque on any system is always equal to the *total* torque on the system; the sum of all internal torques of any system is always 0 (this is the rotational analogue of Newton's third law of motion).
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Therefore, for an isolated system (where there is no net external torque), the *total* torque on the system must be 0, which means that the total angular momentum of the system is constant.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The change in angular momentum for a particular interaction is called **angular impulse**, sometimes **twirl**.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Angular impulse is the angular analog of (linear) impulse.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The trivial case of the angular momentum L of a body in an orbit is given by $L=2\pi Mfr^{2}$ where M is the mass of the orbiting object, f is the orbit's frequency and r is the orbit's radius.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The angular momentum L of a uniform rigid sphere rotating around its axis, instead, is given by $L={\frac {4}{5}}\pi Mfr^{2}$ where M is the sphere's mass, f is the frequency of rotation and r is the sphere's radius.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Thus, for example, the orbital angular momentum of the Earth with respect to the Sun is about 2.66 × 1040 kg⋅m2⋅s−1, while its rotational angular momentum is about 7.05 × 1033 kg⋅m2⋅s−1.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] In the case of a uniform rigid sphere rotating around its axis, if, instead of its mass, its density is known, the angular momentum L is given by $L={\frac {16}{15}}\pi ^{2}\rho fr^{5}$ where $\rho$ is the sphere's density, f is the frequency of rotation and r is the sphere's radius.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] In the simplest case of a spinning disk, the angular momentum L is given by $L=\pi Mfr^{2}$ where M is the disk's mass, f is the frequency of rotation and r is the disk's radius.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Just as for angular velocity, there are two special types of angular momentum of an object: the **spin angular momentum** is the angular momentum about the object's center of mass, while the **orbital angular momentum** is the angular momentum about a chosen center of rotation.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The Earth has an orbital angular momentum by nature of revolving around the Sun, and a spin angular momentum by nature of its daily rotation around the polar axis.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The total angular momentum is the sum of the spin and orbital angular momenta.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] In the case of the Earth the primary conserved quantity is the total angular momentum of the Solar System because angular momentum is exchanged to a small but important extent among the planets and the Sun.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The orbital angular momentum vector of a point particle is always parallel and directly proportional to its orbital angular velocity vector **ω**, where the constant of proportionality depends on both the mass of the particle and its distance from origin.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The spin angular momentum vector of a rigid body is proportional but not always parallel to the spin angular velocity vector **Ω**, making the constant of proportionality a second-rank tensor rather than a scalar.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Angular momentum is a vector quantity (more precisely, a pseudovector) that represents the product of a body's rotational inertia and rotational velocity (in radians/sec) about a particular axis.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] However, if the particle's trajectory lies in a single plane, it is sufficient to discard the vector nature of angular momentum, and treat it as a scalar (more precisely, a pseudoscalar).
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Angular momentum can be considered a rotational analog of linear momentum.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Unlike mass, which depends only on amount of matter, moment of inertia depends also on the position of the axis of rotation and the distribution of the matter.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Unlike linear velocity, which does not depend upon the choice of origin, orbital angular velocity is always measured with respect to a fixed origin.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Therefore, strictly speaking, L should be referred to as the angular momentum *relative to that center*.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] the product of the radius of rotation r and the linear momentum of the particle $p=mv$ , where $v=r\omega$ is the linear (tangential) speed.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] This simple analysis can also apply to non-circular motion if one uses the component of the motion perpendicular to the radius vector: $L=rmv_{\perp },$ where $v_{\perp }=v\sin(\theta )$ is the perpendicular component of the motion.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Expanding, $L=rmv\sin(\theta ),$ rearranging, $L=r\sin(\theta )mv,$ and reducing, angular momentum can also be expressed, $L=r_{\perp }mv,$ where $r_{\perp }=r\sin(\theta )$ is the length of the *moment arm*, a line dropped perpendicularly from the origin onto the path of the particle.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] It is this definition, (length of moment arm) × (linear momentum), to which the term *moment of momentum* refers.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Another approach is to define angular momentum as the conjugate momentum (also called **canonical momentum**) of the angular coordinate $\phi$ expressed in the Lagrangian of the mechanical system.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Consider a mechanical system with a mass m constrained to move in a circle of radius r in the absence of any external force field.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] By retaining this vector nature of angular momentum, the general nature of the equations is also retained, and can describe any sort of three-dimensional motion about the center of rotation – circular, linear, or otherwise.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] By the definition of the cross product, the $\mathbf {L}$ vector is perpendicular to both $\mathbf {r}$ and $\mathbf {p}$ .
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] It is directed perpendicular to the plane of angular displacement, as indicated by the right-hand rule – so that the angular velocity is seen as counter-clockwise from the head of the vector.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Conversely, the $\mathbf {L}$ vector defines the plane in which $\mathbf {r}$ and $\mathbf {p}$ lie.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Angular momentum can be described as the rotational analog of linear momentum.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Like linear momentum it involves elements of mass and displacement.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Unlike linear momentum it also involves elements of position and shape.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Many problems in physics involve matter in motion about some certain point in space, be it in actual rotation about it, or simply moving past it, where it is desired to know what effect the moving matter has on the point—can it exert energy upon it or perform work about it?
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Energy, the ability to do work, can be stored in matter by setting it in motion—a combination of its inertia and its displacement.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Inertia is measured by its mass, and displacement by its velocity.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Their product, ${\begin{aligned}({\text{amount of inertia}})\times ({\text{amount of displacement}})&={\text{amount of (inertia⋅displacement)}}\\{\text{mass}}\times {\text{velocity}}&={\text{momentum}}\\m\times v&=p\\\end{aligned}}$ is the matter's momentum.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Referring this momentum to a central point introduces a complication: the momentum is not applied to the point directly.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] For instance, a particle of matter at the outer edge of a wheel is, in effect, at the end of a lever of the same length as the wheel's radius, its momentum turning the lever about the center point.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] This imaginary lever is known as the *moment arm*.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] It has the effect of multiplying the momentum's effort in proportion to its length, an effect known as a *moment*.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The equation $L=rmv$ combines a moment (a mass m turning moment arm r ) with a linear (straight-line equivalent) speed v .
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Linear speed referred to the central point is simply the product of the distance r and the angular speed $\omega$ versus the point: $v=r\omega ,$ another moment.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Hence, angular momentum contains a double moment: $L=rmr\omega .$ Simplifying slightly, $L=r^{2}m\omega ,$ the quantity $r^{2}m$ is the particle's moment of inertia, sometimes called the second moment of mass.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The direction of momentum is related to the direction of the velocity for linear movement.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The direction of angular momentum is related to the angular velocity of the rotation.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Because moment of inertia is a crucial part of the spin angular momentum, the latter necessarily includes all of the complications of the former, which is calculated by multiplying elementary bits of the mass by the squares of their distances from the center of rotation.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Therefore, the total moment of inertia, and the angular momentum, is a complex function of the configuration of the matter about the center of rotation and the orientation of the rotation for the various bits.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] For a rigid body, for instance a wheel or an asteroid, the orientation of rotation is simply the position of the rotation axis versus the matter of the body.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] It may or may not pass through the center of mass, or it may lie completely outside of the body.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] For the same body, angular momentum may take a different value for every possible axis about which rotation may take place.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] It reaches a minimum when the axis passes through the center of mass.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] For a collection of objects revolving about a center, for instance all of the bodies of the Solar System, the orientations may be somewhat organized, as is the Solar System, with most of the bodies' axes lying close to the system's axis.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Their orientations may also be completely random.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] In brief, the more mass and the farther it is from the center of rotation (the longer the moment arm), the greater the moment of inertia, and therefore the greater the angular momentum for a given angular velocity.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] In many cases the moment of inertia, and hence the angular momentum, can be simplified by, $I=k^{2}m,$ where k is the radius of gyration, the distance from the axis at which the entire mass m may be considered as concentrated.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Angular momentum's dependence on position and shape is reflected in its units versus linear momentum: kg⋅m2/s or N⋅m⋅s for angular momentum versus kg⋅m/s or N⋅s for linear momentum.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] When calculating angular momentum as the product of the moment of inertia times the angular velocity, the angular velocity must be expressed in radians per second, where the radian assumes the dimensionless value of unity.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] (When performing dimensional analysis, it may be productive to use orientational analysis which treats radians as a base unit, but this is not done in the International system of units).
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The units of angular momentum can be interpreted as torque⋅time.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] An object with angular momentum of *L* N⋅m⋅s can be reduced to zero angular velocity by an angular impulse of *L* N⋅m⋅s.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The plane perpendicular to the axis of angular momentum and passing through the center of mass is sometimes called the *invariable plane*, because the direction of the axis remains fixed if only the interactions of the bodies within the system, free from outside influences, are considered.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] One such plane is the invariable plane of the Solar System.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Newton's second law of motion can be expressed mathematically, $\mathbf {F} =m\mathbf {a} ,$ or force = mass × acceleration.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Note that the torque is not necessarily proportional or parallel to the angular acceleration (as one might expect).
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The reason for this is that the moment of inertia of a particle can change with time, something that cannot occur for ordinary mass.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The conservation of angular momentum is used in analyzing *central force motion*.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] If the net force on some body is directed always toward some point, the *center*, then there is no torque on the body with respect to the center, as all of the force is directed along the radius vector, and none is perpendicular to the radius.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Mathematically, torque ${\boldsymbol {\tau }}=\mathbf {r} \times \mathbf {F} =\mathbf {0} ,$ because in this case $\mathbf {r}$ and $\mathbf {F}$ are parallel vectors.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Therefore, the angular momentum of the body about the center is constant.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] This is the case with gravitational attraction in the orbits of planets and satellites, where the gravitational force is always directed toward the primary body and orbiting bodies conserve angular momentum by exchanging distance and velocity as they move about the primary.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Central force motion is also used in the analysis of the Bohr model of the atom.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] For a planet, angular momentum is distributed between the spin of the planet and its revolution in its orbit, and these are often exchanged by various mechanisms.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The conservation of angular momentum in the Earth–Moon system results in the transfer of angular momentum from Earth to Moon, due to tidal torque the Moon exerts on the Earth.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] This in turn results in the slowing down of the rotation rate of Earth, at about 65.7 nanoseconds per day, and in gradual increase of the radius of Moon's orbit, at about 3.82 centimeters per year.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The conservation of angular momentum explains the angular acceleration of an ice skater as they bring their arms and legs close to the vertical axis of rotation.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] By bringing part of the mass of their body closer to the axis, they decrease their body's moment of inertia.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Because angular momentum is the product of moment of inertia and angular velocity, if the angular momentum remains constant (is conserved), then the angular velocity (rotational speed) of the skater must increase.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The same phenomenon results in extremely fast spin of compact stars (like white dwarfs, neutron stars and black holes) when they are formed out of much larger and slower rotating stars.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Conservation is not always a full explanation for the dynamics of a system but is a key constraint.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] For example, a spinning top is subject to gravitational torque making it lean over and change the angular momentum about the nutation axis, but neglecting friction at the point of spinning contact, it has a conserved angular momentum about its spinning axis, and another about its precession axis.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Also, in any planetary system, the planets, star(s), comets, and asteroids can all move in numerous complicated ways, but only so that the angular momentum of the system is conserved.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Noether's theorem states that every conservation law is associated with a symmetry (invariant) of the underlying physics.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The symmetry associated with conservation of angular momentum is rotational invariance.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The fact that the physics of a system is unchanged if it is rotated by any angle about an axis implies that angular momentum is conserved.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Indeed, given initial conditions of position and velocity for every point, and the forces at such a condition, one may use Newton's second law to calculate the second derivative of position, and solving for this gives full information on the development of the physical system with time.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Note, however, that this is no longer true in quantum mechanics, due to the existence of particle spin, which is an angular momentum that cannot be described by the cumulative effect of point-like motions in space.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] As an example, consider decreasing of the moment of inertia, e.g. when a figure skater is pulling in their hands, speeding up the circular motion.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Using this, we see that the change requires an energy of: $dE=d\left({\tfrac {1}{2}}I\cdot \omega ^{2}\right)={\tfrac {1}{2}}dI\cdot \omega ^{2}+I\cdot \omega \cdot d\omega =-{\tfrac {1}{2}}dI\cdot \omega ^{2}$ so that a decrease in the moment of inertia requires investing energy.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] This can be compared to the work done as calculated using Newton's laws.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Let us observe a point of mass *m*, whose position vector relative to the center of motion is perpendicular to the z-axis at a given point of time, and is at a distance *z*.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] For a non-pointlike body one must integrate over this, with *m* replaced by the mass density per unit *z*.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] This gives: $dW=-{\tfrac {1}{2}}dI\cdot \omega ^{2}$ which is exactly the energy required for keeping the angular momentum conserved.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Note, that the above calculation can also be performed per mass, using kinematics only.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] However, this is different when pulling the palms closer to the body: The acceleration due to rotation now increases the speed; but because of the rotation, the increase in speed does not translate to a significant speed inwards, but to an increase of the rotation speed.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] In classical mechanics it can be shown that the rotational invariance of action functionals implies conservation of angular momentum.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The action is defined in classical physics as a functional of positions, $x_{i}(t)$ often represented by the use of square brackets, and the final and initial times.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] If the action is invariant of an infinitesimal transformation, it can be mathematically stated as: ${\textstyle \delta S=S\left([x_{i}+\delta x_{i}];t_{1},t_{2}\right)-S\left([x_{i}];t_{1},t_{2}\right)=0}$ .
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] This corresponds to the conservation of angular momentum throughout the motion.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] In Lagrangian mechanics, angular momentum for rotation around a given axis, is the conjugate momentum of the generalized coordinate of the angle around the same axis.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] For example, $L_{z}$ , the angular momentum around the z axis, is: $L_{z}={\frac {\partial {\cal {L}}}{\partial {\dot {\theta }}_{z}}}$ where ${\cal {L}}$ is the Lagrangian and $\theta _{z}$ is the angle around the z axis.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Note that ${\dot {\theta }}_{z}$ , the time derivative of the angle, is the angular velocity $\omega _{z}$ .
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Since the lagrangian is dependent upon the angles of the object only through the potential, we have: ${\frac {d{L_{z}}_{i}}{dt}}={\frac {\partial {\cal {L}}}{\partial {{\theta _{z}}_{i}}}}=-{\frac {\partial V}{\partial {{\theta _{z}}_{i}}}}$ which is the torque on the *i*th object.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Suppose the system is invariant to rotations, so that the potential is independent of an overall rotation by the angle *θ*z (thus it may depend on the angles of objects only through their differences, in the form $V({\theta _{z}}_{i},{\theta _{z}}_{j})=V({\theta _{z}}_{i}-{\theta _{z}}_{j})$ ).
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] We therefore get for the total angular momentum: ${\frac {dL_{z}}{dt}}=-{\frac {\partial V}{\partial {\theta _{z}}}}=0$ And thus the angular momentum around the z-axis is conserved.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] This analysis can be repeated separately for each axis, giving conservation of the angular momentum vector.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] However, the angles around the three axes cannot be treated simultaneously as generalized coordinates, since they are not independent; in particular, two angles per point suffice to determine its position.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] While it is true that in the case of a rigid body, fully describing it requires, in addition to three translational degrees of freedom, also specification of three rotational degrees of freedom; however these cannot be defined as rotations around the Cartesian axes (see Euler angles).
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] This caveat is reflected in quantum mechanics in the non-trivial commutation relations of the different components of the angular momentum operator.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Equivalently, in Hamiltonian mechanics the Hamiltonian can be described as a function of the angular momentum.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] And so we get the same results as in the Lagrangian formalism.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] This form of the kinetic energy part of the Hamiltonian is useful in analyzing central potential problems, and is easily transformed to a quantum mechanical work frame (e.g. in the hydrogen atom problem).
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] While in classical mechanics the language of angular momentum can be replaced by Newton's laws of motion, it is particularly useful for motion in central potential such as planetary motion in the solar system.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Thus, the orbit of a planet in the solar system is defined by its energy, angular momentum and angles of the orbit major axis relative to a coordinate frame.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] In astrodynamics and celestial mechanics, a quantity closely related to angular momentum is defined as $\mathbf {h} =\mathbf {r} \times \mathbf {v} ,$ called *specific angular momentum*.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Note that $\mathbf {L} =m\mathbf {h} .$ Mass is often unimportant in orbital mechanics calculations, because motion of a body is determined by gravity.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The primary body of the system is often so much larger than any bodies in motion about it that the gravitational effect of the smaller bodies on it can be neglected; it maintains, in effect, constant velocity.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The motion of all bodies is affected by its gravity in the same way, regardless of mass, and therefore all move approximately the same way under the same conditions.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Angular momentum is also an extremely useful concept for describing rotating rigid bodies such as a gyroscope or a rocky planet.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] For a continuous mass distribution with density function *ρ*(**r**), a differential volume element *dV* with position vector **r** within the mass has a mass element *dm* = *ρ*(**r**)*dV*.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] In the derivation which follows, integrals similar to this can replace the sums for the case of continuous mass.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] For a collection of particles in motion about an arbitrary origin, it is informative to develop the equation of angular momentum by resolving their motion into components about their own center of mass and about the origin.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The first term is the angular momentum of the center of mass relative to the origin.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Similar to *§ Single particle*, below, it is the angular momentum of one particle of mass *M* at the center of mass moving with velocity **V**.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The second term is the angular momentum of the particles moving relative to the center of mass, similar to *§ Fixed center of mass*, below.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The result is general—the motion of the particles is not restricted to rotation or revolution about the origin or center of mass.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The particles need not be individual masses, but can be elements of a continuous distribution, such as a solid body.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] In modern (20th century) theoretical physics, angular momentum (not including any intrinsic angular momentum – see below) is described using a different formalism, instead of a classical pseudovector.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] In this formalism, angular momentum is the 2-form Noether charge associated with rotational invariance.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] As a result, angular momentum is generally not conserved locally for general curved spacetimes, unless they have rotational symmetry; whereas globally the notion of angular momentum itself only makes sense if the spacetime is asymptotically flat.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] In classical mechanics, the angular momentum of a particle can be reinterpreted as a plane element: $\mathbf {L} =\mathbf {r} \wedge \mathbf {p} \,,$ in which the exterior product (∧) replaces the cross product (×) (these products have similar characteristics but are nonequivalent).
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] This has the advantage of a clearer geometric interpretation as a plane element, defined using the vectors **x** and **p**, and the expression is true in any number of dimensions.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] The angular velocity can also be defined as an anti-symmetric second order tensor, with components *ωij*.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] Again, this equation in **L** and ***ω*** as tensors is true in any number of dimensions.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] This equation also appears in the geometric algebra formalism, in which **L** and ***ω*** are bivectors, and the moment of inertia is a mapping between them.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p01] In each of the above cases, for a system of particles the total angular momentum is just the sum of the individual particle angular momenta, and the center of mass is for the system.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] In quantum mechanics, angular momentum (like other quantities) is expressed as an operator, and its one-dimensional projections have quantized eigenvalues.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Angular momentum is subject to the Heisenberg uncertainty principle, implying that at any time, only one projection (also called "component") can be measured with definite precision; the other two then remain uncertain.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Because of this, the axis of rotation of a quantum particle is undefined.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Quantum particles *do* possess a type of non-orbital angular momentum called "spin", but this angular momentum does not correspond to a spinning motion.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] In relativistic quantum mechanics the above relativistic definition becomes a tensorial operator.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] The classical definition of angular momentum as $\mathbf {L} =\mathbf {r} \times \mathbf {p}$ can be carried over to quantum mechanics, by reinterpreting **r** as the quantum position operator and **p** as the quantum momentum operator.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] **L** is then an operator, specifically called the *orbital angular momentum operator*.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] The components of the angular momentum operator satisfy the commutation relations of the Lie algebra SO(3).
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Indeed, these operators are precisely the infinitesimal action of the rotation group on the quantum Hilbert space.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] However, in quantum physics, there is another type of angular momentum, called *spin angular momentum*, represented by the spin operator **S**.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Spin is often depicted as a particle literally spinning around an axis, but this is a misleading and inaccurate picture: spin is an intrinsic property of a particle, unrelated to any sort of motion in space and fundamentally different from orbital angular momentum.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] All elementary particles have a characteristic spin, which is nonzero for all elementary particles other than the Higgs boson (which has spin 0, making it the only known elementary scalar boson).
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] For example, electrons have "spin 1/2" (this actually means "spin ħ/2"), photons have "spin 1" (this actually means "spin ħ"), and pi-mesons have spin 0.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Finally, there is total angular momentum **J**, which combines both the spin and orbital angular momentum of all particles and fields.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] (For one particle, **J** = **L** + **S**.) Conservation of angular momentum applies to **J**, but not to **L** or **S**; for example, the spin–orbit interaction allows angular momentum to transfer back and forth between **L** and **S**, with the total remaining constant.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Electrons and photons need not have integer-based values for total angular momentum, but can also have half-integer values.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] In molecules the total angular momentum **F** is the sum of the rovibronic (orbital) angular momentum **N**, the electron spin angular momentum **S**, and the nuclear spin angular momentum **I**.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] For electronic singlet states the rovibronic angular momentum is denoted **J** rather than **N**.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] As explained by Van Vleck, the components of the molecular rovibronic angular momentum referred to molecule-fixed axes have different commutation relations from those for the components about space-fixed axes.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] In quantum mechanics, angular momentum is quantized – that is, it cannot vary continuously, but only in "quantum leaps" between certain allowed values.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] The reduced Planck constant $\hbar$ is tiny by everyday standards, about 10−34 J s, and therefore this quantization does not noticeably affect the angular momentum of macroscopic objects.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] However, it is very important in the microscopic world.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] For example, the structure of electron shells and subshells in chemistry is significantly affected by the quantization of angular momentum.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Quantization of angular momentum was first postulated by Niels Bohr in his model of the atom and was later predicted by Erwin Schrödinger in his Schrödinger equation.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] In the definition $\mathbf {L} =\mathbf {r} \times \mathbf {p}$ , six operators are involved: The position operators $r_{x}$ , $r_{y}$ , $r_{z}$ , and the momentum operators $p_{x}$ , $p_{y}$ , $p_{z}$ .
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] However, the Heisenberg uncertainty principle tells us that it is not possible for all six of these quantities to be known simultaneously with arbitrary precision.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Therefore, there are limits to what can be known or measured about a particle's angular momentum.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] It turns out that the best that one can do is to simultaneously measure both the angular momentum vector's magnitude and its component along one axis.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] The uncertainty is closely related to the fact that different components of an angular momentum operator do not commute, for example $L_{x}L_{y}\neq L_{y}L_{x}$ .
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] As mentioned above, orbital angular momentum **L** is defined as in classical mechanics: $\mathbf {L} =\mathbf {r} \times \mathbf {p}$ , but *total* angular momentum **J** is defined in a different, more basic way: **J** is defined as the "generator of rotations".
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] More specifically, **J** is defined so that the operator $R({\hat {n}},\phi )\equiv \exp \left(-{\frac {i}{\hbar }}\phi \,\mathbf {J} \cdot {\hat {\mathbf {n} }}\right)$ is the rotation operator that takes any system and rotates it by angle $\phi$ about the axis ${\hat {\mathbf {n} }}$ .
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] (The "exp" in the formula refers to operator exponential.) To put this the other way around, whatever our quantum Hilbert space is, we expect that the rotation group SO(3) will act on it.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] There is then an associated action of the Lie algebra so(3) of SO(3); the operators describing the action of so(3) on our Hilbert space are the (total) angular momentum operators.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] The relationship between the angular momentum operator and the rotation operators is the same as the relationship between Lie algebras and Lie groups in mathematics.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] The close relationship between angular momentum and rotations is reflected in Noether's theorem that proves that angular momentum is conserved whenever the laws of physics are rotationally invariant.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] When describing the motion of a charged particle in an electromagnetic field, the canonical momentum **P** (derived from the Lagrangian for this system) is not gauge invariant.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] As a consequence, the canonical angular momentum **L** = **r** × **P** is not gauge invariant either.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Instead, the momentum that is physical, the so-called *kinetic momentum* (used throughout this article), is (in SI units) $\mathbf {p} =m\mathbf {v} =\mathbf {P} -e\mathbf {A}$ where *e* is the electric charge of the particle and **A** the magnetic vector potential of the electromagnetic field.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] The interplay with quantum mechanics is discussed further in the article on canonical commutation relations.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] The above identities are valid *locally*, i.e. in each space point $\mathbf {r}$ in a given moment t .
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Tropical cyclones and other related weather phenomena involve conservation of angular momentum in order to explain the dynamics.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Winds revolve slowly around low pressure systems, mainly due to the coriolis effect.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] If the low pressure intensifies and the slowly circulating air is drawn toward the center, the molecules must speed up in order to conserve angular momentum.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] By the time they reach the center, the speeds become destructive.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Johannes Kepler determined the laws of planetary motion without knowledge of conservation of momentum.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] However, not long after his discovery their derivation was determined from conservation of angular momentum.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Planets move more slowly the further they are out in their elliptical orbits, which is explained intuitively by the fact that orbital angular momentum is proportional to the radius of the orbit.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Since the mass does not change and the angular momentum is conserved, the velocity drops.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Tidal acceleration is an effect of the tidal forces between an orbiting natural satellite (e.g. the Moon) and the primary planet that it orbits (e.g.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] The Earth loses angular momentum which is transferred to the Moon such that the overall angular momentum is conserved.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Examples of using conservation of angular momentum for practical advantage are abundant.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] In engines such as steam engines or internal combustion engines, a flywheel is needed to efficiently convert the lateral motion of the pistons to rotational motion.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Inertial navigation systems explicitly use the fact that angular momentum is conserved with respect to the inertial frame of space.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Inertial navigation is what enables submarine trips under the polar ice cap, but are also crucial to all forms of modern navigation.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Rifled bullets use the stability provided by conservation of angular momentum to be more true in their trajectory.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] The invention of rifled firearms and cannons gave their users significant strategic advantage in battle, and thus were a technological turning point in history.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] However, his geometric proof of the law of areas is an outstanding example of Newton's genius, and indirectly proves angular momentum conservation in the case of a central force.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] As a planet orbits the Sun, the line between the Sun and the planet sweeps out equal areas in equal intervals of time.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] This had been known since Kepler expounded his second law of planetary motion.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Newton derived a unique geometric proof, and went on to show that the attractive force of the Sun's gravity was the cause of all of Kepler's laws.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] During the first interval of time, an object is in motion from point **A** to point **B**.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Undisturbed, it would continue to point **c** during the second interval.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] When the object arrives at **B**, it receives an impulse directed toward point **S**.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] The impulse gives it a small added velocity toward **S**, such that if this were its only velocity, it would move from **B** to **V** during the second interval.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] By the rules of velocity composition, these two velocities add, and point **C** is found by construction of parallelogram **BcCV**.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Thus the object's path is deflected by the impulse so that it arrives at point **C** at the end of the second interval.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Because the triangles **SBc** and **SBC** have the same base **SB** and the same height **Bc** or **VC**, they have the same area.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] By symmetry, triangle **SBc** also has the same area as triangle **SAB**, therefore the object has swept out equal areas **SAB** and **SBC** in equal times.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] At point **C**, the object receives another impulse toward **S**, again deflecting its path during the third interval from **d** to **D**.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Allowing the time intervals to become ever smaller, the path **ABCDE** approaches indefinitely close to a continuous curve.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Note that because this derivation is geometric, and no specific force is applied, it proves a more general law than Kepler's second law of planetary motion.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] It shows that the Law of Areas applies to any central force, attractive or repulsive, continuous or non-continuous, or zero.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Hence, if the area swept per unit time is constant, then by the triangular area formula ⁠1/2⁠(base)(height), the product (base)(height) and therefore the product *rv*⊥ are constant: if *r* and the base length are decreased, *v*⊥ and height must increase proportionally.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Mass is constant, therefore angular momentum *rmv*⊥ is conserved by this exchange of distance and velocity.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Wherever **C** is eventually located due to the impulse applied at **B**, the product (**SB**)(**VC**), and therefore *rmv*⊥ remain constant.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Another areal proof of conservation of angular momentum for any central force uses Mamikon's sweeping tangents theorem.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Leonhard Euler, Daniel Bernoulli, and Patrick d'Arcy all understood angular momentum in terms of conservation of areal velocity, a result of their analysis of Kepler's second law of planetary motion.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] It is unlikely that they realized the implications for ordinary rotating matter.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] In 1736 Euler, like Newton, touched on some of the equations of angular momentum in his *Mechanica* without further developing them.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Bernoulli wrote in a 1744 letter of a "moment of rotational motion", possibly the first conception of angular momentum as we now understand it.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] In 1799, Pierre-Simon Laplace first realized that a fixed plane was associated with rotation—his *invariable plane*.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Louis Poinsot in 1803 began representing rotations as a line segment perpendicular to the rotation, and elaborated on the "conservation of moments".
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] In 1852 Léon Foucault used a gyroscope in an experiment to display the Earth's rotation.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] In an 1872 edition of the same book, Rankine stated that "The term *angular momentum* was introduced by Mr.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Hayward's article *On a Direct Method of estimating Velocities, Accelerations, and all similar Quantities with respect to Axes moveable in any manner in Space with Applications,* which was introduced in 1856, and published in 1864.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Rankine was mistaken, as numerous publications feature the term starting in the late 18th to early 19th centuries.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] However, Hayward's article apparently was the first use of the term and the concept seen by much of the English-speaking world.
[src:couple-mechanics/angular-momentum-p02] Before this, angular momentum was typically referred to as "momentum of rotation" in English.
[src:couple-mechanics/couple-mechanics] In physics, a **couple** is a pair of forces that are equal in magnitude but opposite in their direction of action.
[src:couple-mechanics/couple-mechanics] A couple produces a pure rotational motion without any translational form.
[src:couple-mechanics/couple-mechanics] The simplest kind of couple consists of two equal and opposite forces whose lines of action do not coincide.
[src:couple-mechanics/couple-mechanics] The forces have a turning effect or moment called a torque about an axis which is normal (perpendicular) to the plane of the forces.
[src:couple-mechanics/couple-mechanics] The SI unit for the torque of the couple is newton metre.
[src:couple-mechanics/couple-mechanics] The magnitude of the torque is equal to *F* • *d*, with the direction of the torque given by the unit vector ${\hat {e}}$ , which is perpendicular to the plane containing the two forces and positive being a counter-clockwise couple.
[src:couple-mechanics/couple-mechanics] The moment of a force is only defined with respect to a certain point P (it is said to be the "moment about P") and, in general, when P is changed, the moment changes.
[src:couple-mechanics/couple-mechanics] However, the moment (torque) of a *couple* is *independent* of the reference point P: Any point will give the same moment.
[src:couple-mechanics/couple-mechanics] In other words, a couple, unlike any more general moments, is a "free vector".
[src:couple-mechanics/couple-mechanics] The proof of this claim is as follows: Suppose there are a set of force vectors **F**1, **F**2, etc. that form a couple, with position vectors (about some origin P), **r**1, **r**2, etc., respectively.
[src:couple-mechanics/couple-mechanics] Now we pick a new reference point P' that differs from P by the vector **r**.
[src:couple-mechanics/couple-mechanics] This proves that the moment is independent of reference point, which is proof that a couple is a free vector.
[src:couple-mechanics/couple-mechanics] A force *F* applied to a rigid body at a distance *d* from the center of mass has the same effect as the same force applied directly to the center of mass and a couple *Cℓ = Fd*.
[src:couple-mechanics/couple-mechanics] The couple produces an angular acceleration of the rigid body at right angles to the plane of the couple.
[src:couple-mechanics/couple-mechanics] The force at the center of mass accelerates the body in the direction of the force without change in orientation.
[src:couple-mechanics/couple-mechanics] Conversely, a couple and a force in the plane of the couple can be replaced by a single force, appropriately located.
[src:couple-mechanics/couple-mechanics] Any couple can be replaced by another in the same plane of the same direction and moment, having any desired force or any desired arm.
[src:couple-mechanics/couple-mechanics] Couples are very important in engineering and the physical sciences.
